Introduction¶

This project would analyse dataset collected from The Movie Database (TMDb), including user ratings and revenue. I will try to answer somes questions from the dataset based on the following categories: popularity, Budget & Revenue, Director, and Production companies

Movie Popularity

  • which movie has the highest popularity?

Budget & Revenue,

  • what are the correlations between different numerical column in the movies dataset?

  • Can the columns with higher correlation be visually proven

  • Does movies with higher budgets has higher revenue?

  • What is the correlation between budget and revenue?

Director

  • Which Director appear most frequently, and who has directed the top 10 movies?

Production Companies:

  • Which Production companies has the highest and lowest movies produced?

Modules to analyse the data include: numpy, pandas, matplotlib, and seaborn

Using def function,

In [31]:
def reg_correlation(x,y,title):
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(12, 8))
    correlation = df_movies[[x,y]].corr().round(2).loc[x,y]
    sns.regplot(x=x, y=y, data=df_movies, ax=ax)
    ax.set_title(title)
    plt.legend([f'Correlation = {correlation}']);

Research Question 3: Movies Directors

  • Which movie Directors appear most frequently, and who has directed the top 10 movies?

To answer this question I will be introducing def function. This function will spill the dataframe from the selected column, which includes a list, downward. it will return a dataframe with spilled columns.

In [36]:
def spilldown(column: str, include: str ='popularity'):
    """
        
    """
    if include:
        filldown = df_movies[[column, include]].explode(column)
        return filldown.groupby(column)[include]\
                        .mean()\
                        .sort_values(ascending=False)
    else:
        return df[[column]].explode(column)
In [37]:
director_pop = spilldown('director')

To Visualize companies with number of movies produced

In [41]:
def pc_popularity_visual(data:pd.DataFrame, title:str = "Company movies popularity"):
    """

    """
    data.plot.barh(figsize=(12, 8))
    plt.ylabel('Production company')
    plt.xlabel('Number of Movies')
    plt.title(title)

Conclusions¶

I have been able to examine and analyse the dataset from the movies database over the years from 1960-2015. I started by cleaning the data in order to analyse properly and to start exploration, I had to start asking some questions which serve as a guide to my analysis. first, I was able to find out that the top 10 movies within the dataset has with highest popularity have the highest revenue, i.e the more popular a movie is, the more revenur it genrate. The movie, Jurassic world appears to have produces over 30% in popularity and has the same time brought in the highest revenues amongst others in the movie industry. I was also able to find out that there are huge correlation between some variables like budget/popularity, budget/revenue, revenue/vote_count and Vote_count/budget, with each of them producing more than 50% correlation value.

In my findings, I got to know that Colin Trevorrow is the only director in the movie dataset who has the highest movies directed with about 17% popularity to his credit while Joe Russo and Anthony Russo follows suit with about 12% popularity. The production compay who has produced the most movies is Universal Studio, Amblim Entertainment, legend Pictures, Fuji Television Network and Dentsu respectively with over 30% movies produced so far while production company with the least number of movies produced is Simcha.

Project limitation¶

Some variables in the dataset couldn't pose any correlation which poses some limitations during the analysis. Also, what we only have for now are the movies database taken between the years 1960 to 2015, so we can't totally rely on it as a yard stck to determine our reasech hypothesis.
